{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504505"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2337"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2337"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.14,0.52,0.07,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116466"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2337"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98465"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"951"},{"type":"tags","id":"1164"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14487"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116466"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of right facial droop noticed by his wife. He has not experienced any weakness or sensory changes in his limbs. He feels lethargic but is otherwise well. He has a medical history of hypertension, type II diabetes mellitus, and myocardial infarction over 20 years ago. He takes metformin, amlodipine, and aspirin regularly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His vital signs are within normal limits. There is reduced blinking of the right eye, and the patient is unable to close his right eye completely or raise that eyebrow. His neurological examination is otherwise normal. Initial CT head shows no evidence of haemorrhage or ischaemic changes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observation","Dual antiplatelet therapy","Prednisolone","Intravenous thrombolysis","Acyclovir"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with Bell\u0027s palsy, a common stroke mimic. The involvement of the forehead (inability to raise the eyebrow) indicates a lower motor neuron (LMN) pattern of facial weakness. When this occurs in isolation and evolves over hours, Bell\u0027s palsy is the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for Bell\u0027s palsy. Oral corticosteroids have been shown to improve outcomes when started within 72 hours of symptom onset. The typical regimen is prednisolone 60 mg daily for five days, then tapered over the next five days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation\u003C/strong\u003E alone (\u0022watch and wait\u0022) would only be suitable if the palsy had been present for more than 72 hours, as the use of prednisolone is not supported by evidence beyond this timeframe. Even then, some clinicians may still consider a trial of corticosteroids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDual antiplatelet therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is a treatment for acute ischaemic stroke or transient ischaemic attack. It is not indicated in this case as the presentation is typical for Bell\u0027s palsy rather than a central nervous system event.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous thrombolysis\u003C/strong\u003E (fibrinolysis) is a treatment for acute ischaemic stroke within 4.5 hours of symptom onset. It is not appropriate for Bell\u0027s palsy and carries significant risks if administered unnecessarily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcyclovir\u003C/strong\u003E (antivirals) has minimal evidence to support its use in the treatment of Bell\u0027s palsy. A Cochrane review showed that the combination of antivirals and corticosteroids had little or no additional benefit compared to corticosteroids alone in Bell\u0027s palsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile Bell\u0027s palsy is the most likely diagnosis, it\u0027s important to note that central pathology can also cause an LMN pattern of weakness, as the facial nerve nuclei are located in the brainstem. A thorough neurological assessment should always be performed to look for additional neurological signs. If atypical features are present, further imaging with MRI should be considered to evaluate for central causes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Facial droop with forehead involvement suggests a lower motor neurone (LMN) lesion.","Bell\u0027s palsy is a common stroke mimic, typically presenting with isolated LMN facial weakness evolving over hours.","Oral prednisolone is the first-line treatment for Bell\u0027s palsy if presented within 72 hours of symptom onset."],"references":["Idiopathic facial nerve (Bell) palsy. In: eTG Complete [online]. 2017. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Gagyor I, Madhok VB, Daly F, Sullivan F. Antiviral treatment for Bell\u0027s palsy (idiopathic facial paralysis). Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews. 2019(9). Available at: https://www.cochranelibrary.com/cdsr/doi/10.1002/14651858.CD001869.pub9/full"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98465"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2337"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98465"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T10:34:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T10:34:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2337"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116466"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/951"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Bell\u0027s palsy","synonyms":["Facial nerve palsy","Antoni\u0027s palsy